Klotz says that he was called Gracchus not on account of any re- lationship to the family of the Gracchi, but because he pretended to defend the people's rights like the Gracchi3 as Orelli had ex- plained it.

Abrami on the occasion quotes a passage from Capitolinus' Life of Antoninus Pius: ‘⁶ Salaria multis subtraxit, quos otiosos vide- bat accipere, dicens nihil esse sordidius quam si rem publicam ii arroderent, qui nihil in eam suo labore conferrent.’' The good emperor was right, and has set us a good example.
